<section class="about" id="about">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section-label">About</span>

    <div class="about-grid">
      <div class="about-content">
        <p>
          Before Gillings, I earned dual degrees from <strong>Duke University</strong> and
          <strong>Duke Kunshan University</strong> in global health and public policy, including
          three years living and studying in China. That experience — watching how policy written
          in one place lands in another — still shapes how I approach this work.
        </p>
        <p>
          My thesis used natural-language processing to analyze more than 2,300 USAID policy
          documents, tracing how U.S. global health priorities shifted across administrations.
          Since then I've worked on the implementation side: HIV/AIDS subawards at USAID,
          hygiene programs at FHI&nbsp;360, and WASH in healthcare facilities at the Water
          Institute at UNC.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm most interested in roles that bridge research, implementation, and donor strategy —
          whether that's with an implementing partner, in public service, or building something new.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="about-education">
        <h3 class="about-education-title">Education</h3>
        <div class="edu-item">
          <span class="edu-degree">MPH, Global Health</span>
          <span class="edu-school">UNC Gillings School of Global Public Health · 2025–2027</span>
          <span class="edu-note">Global Health Concentration Cohort Representative</span>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-item">
          <span class="edu-degree">B.A. Interdisciplinary Studies · B.S. Global Health &amp; Public Policy</span>
          <span class="edu-school">Duke University &amp; Duke Kunshan University · 2021–2025</span>
          <span class="edu-note">Stanback Fellow · Fubon Scholar · 1st Place, HackDKU 2025</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

